        <body>
            <pb n="1R"/>
            <p rend="align(center)"><placeName>Denekamp</placeName> the</p>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <date>1862</date>
            </p>
            <p rend="align(center)">My beloved uncle!</p>
            <p>Now I find me obliged my dear to answer you<lb/> on your writing; and hope that you
                may read these<lb/> rules in the best situation. As for me I am as well<lb/> as
                heart can wish; although one is not always in the<lb/> best order that is naturally;
                then the man is submitted<lb/> to all; and one is often troubled with many
                distempers,<lb/> but that is all ordered so <sic>trough</sic> the omnipotence<lb/>
                of our heavenly Father; and if one is troubled sometimes<lb/> through some adversity
                one must think all what<lb/> God does is <sic>weldone</sic>. Now my dear uncle I
                must<lb/> make you mention, that when we have received your<lb/> portrait it
                    <sic>maked</sic> us a great joy what you well can<lb/> think; and I thank you
                with all my heart that you<lb/> have had the goodness as to send it us. Now can
                I<lb/> see you, and if I regard it I wished you were by us<lb/> then could I look
                you yet better; but I am also content<lb/> with your picture when it can not others.
                Now I can<lb/> write you yet my news. In the month of <date>May</date> a
                dread,<lb/>ful fire <sic>hitted</sic> the city of <placeName><hi rend="underline"
                        >Enschede</hi></placeName> (what is situated<lb/> four hour from us), the
                whole city is destoryed; no single<lb/> house is delivered. My father, my sister and
                I have<lb/> been there to see also these desolation, but what<lb/> a terrible sight!
                all men are out of the city and here<lb/> and there divulged. The number of houses
                what is</p>
            <pb n="1V"/>
            <p>about twelve hundred, three church and one church<lb/> of the Israelites; all the
                sephers are retrieved. My dear<lb/> uncle you have nothing written from my picture
                how<lb/> it liked you; write it me now if you please. Your<lb/> books what you send
                me come well over every month<lb/> and I read in it yet often with great
                pleasure.<lb/> At this moment I <sic>now</sic> nothing more to write you,<lb/>
                another time more thus I must now finish with this<lb/> and I hope that it may be
                sufficient to you. Farewell<lb/> my dear uncle, and wish to receive speedy from you
                a great<lb/> letter. Many times saluted from me and with this<lb/> I make the end;
                and I am with all reverence</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Your affectionate niece</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">
                <persName role="author">Jeanette Elkus</persName>
            </p>
            <p>
                <add>Hebrew</add>
            </p>
